a) Using the average rate of change formula above for the endpoints (-1, f(-1)) and ( 4 , f( 4 )) , we obtain the following answer:
\frac{ f( 4 ) - f(-1) }{4 - (-1)}
= \frac{ 8  + 7  }{4 + 1}
= \frac{ 15}{5 } = 3



b) Using the average rate of change formula above for the endpoints (a, f(a)) and ( b , f(b)) , we obtain the following answer:
\frac{ f(b) - f(a) }{b - a}
= \frac{ (3 b - 4) - (3 a - 4)  }{b - a}
= \frac{ 3 b - 3 a}{b-a}
= \frac{ 3 (b-a) }{b-a} = 3



c) Using the average rate of change formula above for the endpoints (x, f(x)) and ( x+h , f(x+h)) , we obtain the following answer:
\frac{ f(x+h) - f(x) }{(x+h) - x}
= \frac{ (3 (x+h) - 4) - (3 x - 4)  }{h}
= \frac{ 3 x + 3 h -4 - 3 x + 4}{h}
= \frac{ 3 h }{h} = 3

solution.p:
The definition of the derivative is
f'(x)= \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}
This problem gives us the numerator, f(x+h)-f(x).  So,

\frac{-7-5\sqrt{x+h}-(-7-5\sqrt{x})}{h} = \frac{-5\sqrt{x+h} + 5\sqrt{x}}{h} =\frac{(-5\sqrt{x+h} + 5\sqrt{x})(-5\sqrt{x+h} - 5\sqrt{x})}{h(-5\sqrt{x+h} - 5\sqrt{x})} 
= \frac{-25\mathopen{}\left(x+h\right) + 25x}{h(-5\sqrt{x+h} - 5\sqrt{x})} = \frac{25h}{h(-5\sqrt{x+h} - 5\sqrt{x})} = \frac{25h}{-5 h(\sqrt{x+h}+\sqrt{x})} 
Finally, we can divide to get
=\frac{-5}{\sqrt{x+h}+\sqrt{x}}
That means A=-5, while B=C=1.

Lastly, we can use this to calculate:
f'(1)= \frac{-5}{2\sqrt{1}}
f'(2)= \frac{-5}{2\sqrt{2}}
f'(3)= \frac{-5}{2\sqrt{3}}

